The dataset selected comes from Kaggle and is called 'LeagueofLegends.csv'. There are multiple datasets available and a lot of information provided. To narrow down the scope of this project, I have focused on only champion selections and the outcome of the game. This dataset contains 7,620 unique records from competitive matches between 2015 and 2017 from NALCS, EULCS, LCK, LMS, and CBLoL leagues. This dataset also includes matches from the World Championship and the Mid-Season Invititationals. This is important to keep in mind because we will be analyzes data from high ELO players - or those who are at a high level of competition and think differently than most other players. As such, this analysis could be helpful for same ELO players but might not be helpful for lower ELO players who might act differently in game.

The next step is to convert all my champion selection data into numerical form. This will make it easier for any computer programs to read and use. The way I went about doing this was factorizing the champions and then saving the factors in a list, adding them back into the dataset with one game result - blue wins. Having Blue and Red wins are redundant and not necessary. However, it is important to note that we will now be analyzing wins from the perspective of the blue team.

Once this is done, we will also be looking at generic distributions of each column and to also check if the target - 'wins' - is heavily skewed. Heavy skew can make our algorithms really good at predicting for the direction of the skew and not great at handling anything else.

Given the nature of the game, we expect some skewing in the champion selection because not all champions are fit for all roles.

The model we will use today is XGBClassifier, with reasonable defaults set. I have converted the predictions from probability to binary to match the format of the test set. The AUC of the ROC is not great for this model. The dotted blue line represents a performance no better than randomly guessing. Our model does slightly better than randomly guessing, but not by much.

In [47]:
model_XGB = XGBClassifier(learning_rate = 0.01,
                         n_estimators = 1000,
                         max_depth = 3,
                         subsample = 0.8,
                         colsample_bytree = 1,
                          gamma = 1)
model_XGB.fit(X_train, y_train)
acc_XGB= round(model_XGB.score(X_train,y_train)*100,2)
print("Model accuracy in the training sample is :",acc_XGB,"%")

acc_XGB_test = round(model_XGB.score(X_test, y_test) * 100, 2)
print("Model accuracy in test sample is: ", acc_XGB_test, "%")

y_pred_probx = model_XGB.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

print(y_pred_probx)
model_binary = np.vectorize(lambda i: int(i>= 0.5))(y_pred_probx)
        
print(model_binary)


fpr, tpr, t = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, model_binary)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, model_binary)
plt.plot(fpr,tpr, color = 'red', label = 'AUC = ' + str(round(auc,4)))
plt.plot([0,1], [0,1], color = 'blue', linestyle = '--', label = 'Baseline')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('XGBClassifier')
plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
plt.figure(figsize = (100,90))
plt.show()
print(classification_report(y_test,model_binary))
